- MAIN ASPECTS: Classes, objects, access modifiers, inheritence, constructor, encapsulation, abstraction, polymorphism.
    - Class -> More like a blueprint/template of an object. 
        -> Has member functions and data members
        -> No physical existence.
        -> Eg: Fruits - CLASS 
    - Object -> Instance of a class. 
        -> Physical existence hota hai. 
        -> has properties and behaviours.  
        -> Eg: Apple, Mango, Orange - OBJECTS 
    [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/oops/Student.java]
    - 4 MAJOR PILLARS -> Encapsulation, Inheritence, Polymorphism and Abstraction. 
    - Inheritence -> reusing the functionalities of an existing class in a new class.
        -> Existing class - parent class / base class 
        -> New class - child class / derived class
        -> Child class will inherit all data members and member functions of parent class. 
    - Polymorphism -> existing in many forms with same name.
        -> Achieved by using method overloading and method overidding. 
        -> Method overloading is performed in the same class. 
        -> Method Overidding requires inheritence prop (both parent and child class).
    - Abstraction -> hiding imp implementation details and functionalities. 
        -> Achieved by using abstract classes and interfaces. 
        -> eg. Car => performs abstraction 
    - Encapsulation -> binding all DMs and MFs as a single unit. 
        -> Imp feature here is:- DATA HIDING. <implements info hiding - fields/DMs>
        -> eg. Class where DMs are private and MFs are public where we access data via getter-setters. 
    - Constructors -> object created and its gets automatically called. 
        -> Matches the name of class 
        -> no return type 
        -> Tried making all different constructors based on access modifiers. 
        -> public - object can be created from anywheree 
        -> protected - object can be created only in same package & sub-classes 
        -> default - object can be created only in same package `
        -> private - same class 
    
- KEY POINTERS REQUIRED: 
    - CLASS -> FIELDS + METHODS
        -> Uses . operator to access attributes. 
            -> ObjectReference.variableName;
            -> ObjectReference.MethodName();
        -> FIELDS: 
            -> data members
            -> {access_modifier} {data-type} attribute_name;
            -> if static - no need of object (gets stored in METHOD AREA).
            -> if not static - need object to access it. [SAM<DOUBT>]
            -> if a field is marked as [FINAL], then trying to change it will give [COMPILATION-ERROR].
        -> METHODS: 
            -> member functions
            -> {access_modifier} {return-type} method_name(attributes list) {....}
            -> if static - definition is stored in METHOD AREA. 
                -> stores its local vars in stack memory just like normal method when invoked. 
                -> ACCESSING - {class-name}.{method-name}(params)
            -> if not static - need object to invoke it.
                -> ACCESSING - obj.method (params)
            -> All methods can access all the fields of the same class irrespective of its access modifier. 
    - Instance Variables -> non-static data members. stored in heap memory within object area. 
        -> Lifetime - till object is there in heap memory.
    - Class Variables -> Static data members. 
        -> Lifetime - till class definition is loaded in memory.
    - Local Variables -> eg. defined in a method.
        -> Lifetime - till method ends. 
    - Access Modifiers -> default, public , protected, private 
        -> Default - no accesss modifier is written. 
    - this -> reference to the object of the current cls. 
        -> Differentiates instance vars from local vars
        -> this.age = age 
        -> this(4) => is used to call any other constructor from a constructor of same class. => EXPLICIT CONSTRUCTOR INVOCATION.
    - finalize() -> its called for cleanup process and allows objects to terminate properly. 
        -> JVM may/maynot call it before object destruction. 
        -> Garbage Collection is automatically done by JVM. 
            -> Any unreachable allocated heap memory is eligible for GC.
        -> Depreciated now due to its unpredictability. 

