    - BASIC INFO: 
        -> package declaration should be at the top. 
        -> import statements should be next. 
        -> file can have only one public cls. 
        -> file can have multiple non public classes. 
        -> class declaration should only be after package declaration and then import statements. 
        -> By default, [FIELDS] in Interface are [public-static-final]    
            -> [WHY??] - Interfaces fields are used by classes (so needs to be public.), interfaces dont have objects (so static.), declared by interfaces cant be changed. its a contract (so final.)
        -> By default, [METHODS] in Interface are [public-abstract]
            -> [WHY??] - Interface Methods are implemented by classes (so needs to be public.), interface methods must be implemented (so abstract.)
        -> Classes and interface cannot be private or protected. 
        -> Classes can have protected methods and fields. but interfaces cannot. 
            -> [WHY??] - Methods of class can still be invoked using getters-setters. same with fields. 
            -> But Interface is a contract, it can implemented anywhere, within or out the package. so it needs to be public abstract(methods) and public static final (fields). 

    - PASS BY VALUE and PASS BY REFERENCE: 
        -> Java has only pass-by-value. not pass-by-reference. 
        -> If we pass an var as param, it will simply create another local var and store it in. 
        -> If we pass a reference as param, it will create another ref var and store that address in it. 
        -> So no pass by reference.
        -> Unlike C++ which used to point to same var which was passed as param using concept of REFERENCE VAR.
    - PASSING VAR LENGTH ARGUMENTS:- 
        -> only one such argument can be used. 
        -> should be the last one. 
        -> uses ellipsis (...)
        -> eg: double... numbers
        -> passed methodName(3,5,6.7,45,4.6) => internally a double array will be created in heap memory and ref gets stored in stack memory - in ref var numbers. 
        -> Suppose, if we have an array with no reference var in stack memory then that array is not reachable. ELIGIBLE FOR GARBAGE COLLECTION....
    - FINAL KEYWORD: 
        -> VARIABLE - we cannot change its value. 
        -> METHOD - we cannot override / change its implementation. 
        -> CLASS - no child (extend / implements)

